The King Salman Humanitarian Aid and Relief Centre, Saudi Arabia, in collaboration with the Albasar International Foundation (Makkah Specialist Eye Hospital), Kano, has sponsored free eye procedures on 4,000 indigent patients in Kano and Bauchi states. The foundation, which manages the Makkah Specialist Hospital, is a charitable organisation working for blindness prevention, with emphasis on Africa and Asia. Under the regional office in Nigeria and the Niger Republic, the foundation manages Makkah Specialist Hospital in Kano and Bauchi states in Nigeria, as well as Maradi in the Niger Republic. The Regional Director of the Hospital (Nigeria/Niger), Dr Mohieldin Elbadawi, while briefing journalists in Kano on Thursday, said 2,800 of the beneficiaries were in Kano, while the others were in Bauchi. Elbadawi stated that the programme simultaneously commenced at Makkah Specialist Hospital on Tuesday in Kano and Bauchi and had so far conducted the surgery on more than 150 patients. He added that from 1994 to 2014, a total of 81 free eye camps were conducted, during which 394,243 patients were screened, 33,781 surgeries carried out and 80,555 patients issued with optical glasses. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com